from sklearn.decomposition import PCA 
pca = PCA(n_components = data_sc.shape[1])
pca_data = pca.fit_transform(data_sc)
exp_var_ratio= pca.explained_variance_ratio_
exp_var_ratio.round(3)

cum_var=exp_var_ratio[0]
itr=2 # defined as two as first pc1 variance defined outside the loop
for j in exp_var_ratio[1:]:
    cum_var=cum_var+j
    if cum_var >= 0.95:
        break
    itr=itr+1

print('The number of principle components capturing 95 percent varaition is data is : ',itr,' Varaince explained is ', cum_var)

In [45]:
import numpy as np

# Create a random matrix of size 20 x 8
M = np.random.rand(20, 8)

# Compute Singular Value Decomposition
U, s, Vt = np.linalg.svd(M, full_matrices=False)  # full_matrices=False for economy SVD

# Reconstruct the original matrix using singular values and vectors
reconstructed_M = U @ np.diag(s) @ Vt
In [48]:
diff_norm = np.linalg.norm(M - reconstructed_M, 'fro')
print(f"Frobenius norm of the difference: {diff_norm}")

Frobenius norm of the difference: 4.100998715142304e-14

import numpy as np
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA

# Assuming inp_data_dime contains your input features

# Apply SVD on inp_data_dime
U, s, Vt = np.linalg.svd(inp_data_dime, full_matrices=False)

# Apply PCA on inp_data_dime
pca = PCA()
inp_data_dime_pca = pca.fit_transform(inp_data_dime)

# Compare the SVD-transformed data with PCA-transformed data
# ... (you can use various comparison methods such as visual inspection, correlation, or similarity measures)

# Compare the top 5 singular vectors with eigenvectors
# ... (you can compare the top 5 singular vectors with the principal components obtained from PCA)

# Determine the number of singular vectors required to reproduce 95% of the characteristics of the original data
cumulative_variance = np.cumsum(s**2) / np.sum(s**2)
num_vectors_95 = np.argmax(cumulative_variance >= 0.95) + 1
print(f"Number of singular vectors required to reproduce 95% of original data: {num_vectors_95}")

from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans, AgglomerativeClustering
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Assuming inp_data_dime contains your input features

# Apply PCA to reduce dimensions
pca = PCA(n_components=2)  # Reduce to 2 dimensions for visualization
inp_pca = pca.fit_transform(inp_data_dime)

# Apply K-means clustering
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=3, random_state=42)
kmeans_labels = kmeans.fit_predict(inp_pca)

# Apply Agglomerative clustering
agg_cluster = AgglomerativeClustering(n_clusters=3)
agg_labels = agg_cluster.fit_predict(inp_pca)

# Visualize the clusters
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))

plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.scatter(inp_pca[:, 0], inp_pca[:, 1], c=kmeans_labels, cmap='viridis')
plt.title('K-means Clustering')

plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
plt.scatter(inp_pca[:, 0], inp_pca[:, 1], c=agg_labels, cmap='viridis')
plt.title('Agglomerative Clustering')

plt.show()
